  "title": "Introducing Yourself and Nationalities (Darija)",
  "dialect": "darija",
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Basic Greetings",
          "arabic": "تحية أساسية"
        },
        "text": "Let's start with basic greetings in Moroccan Darija. The most common greeting is 'As-salamu alaykum'. You can also use 'Labas?' to ask 'How are you?' or 'Are you good?'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "السلام عليكم",
            "english": "Hello / Peace be upon you",
            "transliteration": "As-salamu alaykum"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "وعليكم السلام",
            "english": "And upon you be peace (response)",
            "transliteration": "Wa alaykum as-salam"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "لاباس؟",
            "english": "How are you? / Are you good?",
            "transliteration": "Labas?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'How are you?' (Male/Female)",
          "arabic": "كيف حالك؟ (مذكر/مؤنث)"
        },
        "text": "To ask 'How are you?' more specifically, you can use 'Ki dayer?' for a male and 'Ki dayra?' for a female. The response is usually 'Labas, alhamdulillah' (Good, thank God).",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "كي داير؟",
            "english": "How are you? (to a male)",
            "transliteration": "Ki dayer?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "كي دايرة؟",
            "english": "How are you? (to a female)",
            "transliteration": "Ki dayra?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "لاباس، الحمد لله.",
            "english": "Good, thank God.",
            "transliteration": "Labas, alhamdulillah."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Stating Your Name",
          "arabic": "قول اسمك"
        },
        "text": "To say 'My name is...', you use 'Smiti...' followed by your name. This phrase is gender-neutral.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "سميتي أحمد.",
            "english": "My name is Ahmed.",
            "transliteration": "Smiti Ahmed."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "سميتي فاطمة.",
            "english": "My name is Fatima.",
            "transliteration": "Smiti Fatima."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
